	<body>
		<segment id="1" parent="15" relname="span">We must facilitate the active contribution of women in peace operations in Africa.</segment>
		<segment id="2" parent="1" relname="elaboration">We must ensure that United Nations operations are appropriately prepared and equipped to address the needs of women and girls in conflict and post-conflict settings.</segment>
		<segment id="3" parent="4" relname="preparation">New Zealand lies far from the African continent,</segment>
		<segment id="4" parent="10" relname="span">however we strive to make a modest, practical contribution to those efforts.</segment>
		<segment id="5" parent="13" relname="span">New Zealand has long reflected women and peace and security considerations in its doctrine, policy and training for uniformed personnel serving internationally.</segment>
		<segment id="6" parent="12" relname="span">Last November, an all-female New Zealand Defence Force team provided training on the the theme "Operationalization of gender" at the Kofi Annan International Peacekeeping Training Centre in Ghana.</segment>
		<segment id="7" parent="11" relname="conjunction">The training incorporated conflict-prevention techniques through the inclusion of women,</segment>
		<segment id="8" parent="11" relname="conjunction">increasing the employment of women in conflict prevention and resolution processes,</segment>
		<segment id="9" parent="11" relname="conjunction">and women's experiences of leadership in conflict.</segment>
